<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06051334 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06051334 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SCHOOL; MANAGEMENT; CANDIDATE; RECALL; ELECTION; FREMONT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  After all the political sniping and griping surrounding the Fremont UnifiedSchool District recall election, candidates are slated to settle down Mondaynight to discuss educational issues.;    The League of Women Voters issponsoring a candidates night featuring the 10 challengers and one incumbentrunning in the special March 5 recall election.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  The Weekly  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SCHOOL BOARD HOPEFULS TO DISCUSS ISSUES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  School Scene  </MEMO><TEXT>     The race originally was slated to challenge three trustees: Christine Hill,Betty Hollenbeck and James Klent. But Klent resigned Nov. 14. Hollenbeck diedFeb. 2 and wasn't replaced. Klent's appointed replacement, Vernon Smith, sayshe won't campaign to keep Klent's seat.;    That leaves Hill the loneincumbent fighting for her seat. She faces challenges from accountant BettyWooten, tuxedo-shop owner Paul Schechter and retired teacher Loren V. Bainer.;   Those vying for the Klent/Smith seat are attorney James Fallon, engineerJoseph Neff, telephone company trainer Charles DeWitt and copy-shop ownerMarianne Schumaker.;    And competing for Hollenbeck's seat are her ex-husbandJohn Bernstein, businessman John Littau and auditor Cris Raimundo.;    Thoughattention has focused on run-down school buildings in Fremont and last year'steacher strikes, the public may raise other questions at the League of WomenVoters forum. Anyone is welcome to attend.;    The candidate's night will beat 7 p.m. Monday in the City Council Chambers, Fremont City Hall.;    (hbox);   At least one student at Washington High School in Fremont is so fed up aboutthe lack of a gymnasium at her school that she has gone to the top. Not justin Fremont -- but in Sacramento.;    Stephanie Casey, a student council memberat Washington High, wrote to the office of state schools chief Bill Honig totell him how frustrating it is for students to be in high school without agym.;    There's no place for home basketball games, spirit rallies, dances oreven assemblies. Classes are divided into little portable buildings. Theschool is so uncomfortable, she couldn't get students to stay after school fora meeting to discuss the Persian Gulf War. &quot;It's not right,&quot; she complained.;   She's a senior, and wouldn't benefit even if hurry-up plans for a gym bynext September are successful. But she says she wants to make sure futureclasses get a better deal.;    Well, Stephanie got her response. It came in aletter from Robert Agee, deputy state schools superintendent in charge offield services.;    &quot;We understand your frustration with poor facilities andlack of a gymnasium,&quot; Agee wrote to Stephanie. &quot;Unfortunately, state money isscarce and school districts must qualify under a priority system competingwith other needy districts in the state for construction funds. FremontUnified School District has made application for funding, but qualifies foronly a fraction of the amount needed for construction of the gymnasium.&quot;;   Stephanie's gone back to square one. It's time, she said, to get everyonemotivated to do something about this. Just what, though, she doesn't know.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910220  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  482  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday February 20, 199100051334,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>